<body>
  <div id="page">
    <center>
      <h1 class="title">
        Welcome #{@remote_user}!
        <br/>
        This is your new Ruby on Rails website "VideoDemoRailSiteJVWebsite"
      </h1>
    </center>
    <div id="started">
      <h2 class="subtitle">Getting Started</h2>
      <a href="https://w.amazon.com/index.php/RubyEnv" target="_blank">
        <code>RubyEnv</code>
      </a>
      provides access to the standard suite of Ruby / Rails commands. Be sure to specify or default to the
      latest version of ruby, unless you have a good reason not to!
      <pre>
        <preserve>
          
                rubyenv -l
                rubyenv ruby
                rubyenv rake
                rubyenv rails
                rubyenv irb

        </preserve>
      </pre>
      When you want to run Rails commands on your project, simply change into the
      <code>rails-root</code>
      source folder in your website package and run one of the commands above.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      For example, to perform a Rails generate:
      <pre>
        <preserve>
          
                rubyenv rails generate scaffold post subject:string body:text

        </preserve>
      </pre>
      or run the development server on port 3000 (this can be changed in the Rakefile or OpConfig):
      <pre>
        <preserve>
          
                brazil-build server

        </preserve>
      </pre>
      or list/run rake tasks on your Rakefile:
      <pre>
        <preserve>
          
                rubyenv rails -T

        </preserve>
      </pre>
      Any other standard Rails command can be executed in this way, just make sure to run it through
      <code>rubyenv</code>
      following the command examples above and you are set!
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <strong>What if I don't want to use RubyEnv?</strong>
      <br/>
      You'll have to manually reference the binaries on the command line, by doing something ugly like so:
      <pre>
        <preserve>
          
                $(brazil-bootstrap)/jruby9.x/bin/jruby
                $(brazil-bootstrap)/jruby9.x/bin/rake
                $(brazil-bootstrap)/jruby9.x/bin/irb
                $(brazil-bootstrap)/jruby9.x/bin/jruby bin/rails

        </preserve>
      </pre>
      You can create aliases for these commands in your
      <code>~/.zshrc</code>
      (or equivalent) shell config file.
      <br/>
      <br/>
    </div>
    <div id="faq">
      <h2 class="subtitle">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <strong>What is included in my new Ruby on Rails website?</strong>
      <ul>
        <li>Brand spankin' new Ruby on Rails 5.0 application running on Puma</li>
        <li>Midway authentication with automatic SSL redirection</li>
        <li>Odin, QueryLog, and AppConfig support</li>
        <li>Rubocop enabled with friendly defaults</li>
      </ul>
      <strong>Why are rake / rails commands failing?</strong>
      <br/>
      Are you using RubyEnv? Are you running RubyEnv in the rails-root directory? Does RubyEnv have a default ruby version?
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <strong>Why is ActiveRecord not included by default?</strong>
      <br/>
      With Amazon pushing for
      <%= succeed "," do %>
        <a href="https://w.amazon.com/index.php/RollingStone">Rolling Stone</a>
      <% end %>
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <strong>Why is Sentry not included by default?</strong>
      <br/>
      Sentry is being deprecated in favor of Midway. Midway authentication is achieved through
      consuming the
      <a href="https://w.amazon.com/index.php/Midway/HowTo/Deploying_the_SSL_Proxy">
        AWSSSLProxy
      </a>
      environment. You'll have to fully configure it if Octane doesn't do so for you already.
      <br/>
      <br/>
